on and persecution, to her participation in the Harlem Renaissance and beyond. In the 1930s and 1940s she became central, along with Paul Robeson, to the labor movement, and later, in the 1950s, she steered proto-black-feminist activities. Patterson was also crucial to the efforts in the 1970s to free political prisoners, most notably Angela Davis. In the 1980s and 1990s she continued to work as a progressive activist and public intellectual. To read her story is to witness the courage, sacrifice, vision, and discipline of someone who spent decades working to achieve justice and liberation for all.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aAfrican American communistsvBiography. 0aAfrican American women political activistsvBiography. 0aAfrican American women social reformersvBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Women.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2017z978311069634940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822372318zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822372318423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822372318.jpg  a978-3-11-069634-9  DUK eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles